      short: [
        {q:"What is a relative clause? Explain defining and non-defining relative clauses with examples.",a:"RELATIVE CLAUSE:\nA relative clause is a type of subordinate clause that gives more information about a noun. It begins with a relative pronoun (who, whom, whose, which, that) or relative adverb (where, when, why).\n\nDEFINING (RESTRICTIVE) RELATIVE CLAUSE:\n• Gives ESSENTIAL information that identifies the noun\n• Without it, the sentence is unclear or meaningless\n• No commas used\n• Example: 'The man WHO called you is my uncle.' (defines WHICH man)\n\nNON-DEFINING (NON-RESTRICTIVE) RELATIVE CLAUSE:\n• Gives EXTRA/ADDITIONAL information about a noun already identified\n• The sentence still makes sense without it\n• Commas used before and after\n• Cannot use 'that' in non-defining clauses\n• Example: 'My father, WHO is a doctor, works at the city hospital.' (extra info about father)\n\nKEY DIFFERENCE:\n• Defining: 'The student who works hard will pass.' (tells us WHICH student)\n• Non-defining: 'Ravi, who works hard, will pass.' (Ravi already identified — extra info)"},
        {q:"Fill in the blanks with appropriate relative pronouns: who, whom, which, whose, where, when, why.",a:"RELATIVE PRONOUNS AND THEIR USE:\n\n1. WHO — for people (subject)\n   'The woman WHO teaches us is kind.'\n\n2. WHOM — for people (object)\n   'The person WHOM I met yesterday is my cousin.'\n\n3. WHICH — for things and animals\n   'The book WHICH I read was interesting.'\n\n4. THAT — for people, things, animals (especially in defining clauses)\n   'The car THAT broke down was old.'\n\n5. WHOSE — possession (people, things, animals)\n   'The girl WHOSE phone rang was embarrassed.'\n\n6. WHERE — for places\n   'The school WHERE I studied is famous.'\n\n7. WHEN — for time\n   'The year WHEN I was born was 1990.'\n\n8. WHY — for reason\n   'I know the reason WHY she left.'\n\nPRACTICE:\n• The dog __ bit me is aggressive. (which/that)\n• She is the woman __ daughter won the prize. (whose)\n• This is the town __ I grew up. (where)"}
      ],
      long: [
        {q:"Combine the following sentences using relative clauses:\n(a) The boy is my friend. He won the race.\n(b) I bought a book. The book was very expensive.\n(c) She lives in a city. The city is very famous.\n(d) The man spoke well. His speech moved everyone.",a:"COMBINING WITH RELATIVE CLAUSES:\n\n(a) 'The boy who won the race is my friend.'\n(DEFINING: 'who won the race' identifies which boy)\n\n(b) 'The book which/that I bought was very expensive.'\n(DEFINING: 'which I bought' identifies which book)\nOR: 'I bought a book, which was very expensive.'\n(NON-DEFINING: extra information about the book)\n\n(c) 'She lives in a city which/that is very famous.'\n(DEFINING: identifies which city)\nOR: 'She lives in Delhi, which is a very famous city.'\n(NON-DEFINING: Delhi already named, extra info)\n\n(d) 'The man whose speech moved everyone spoke well.'\n(DEFINING: 'whose speech moved everyone' identifies which man)\n\nGRAMMAR RULES APPLIED:\n• 'Who' → for people as subject\n• 'Which/that' → for things\n• 'Whose' → for possession\n• Commas in non-defining clauses\n• 'That' cannot be used in non-defining clauses"}
      ],
      passage: [
        {q:"Read the following passage and answer the questions:\n\n'Mahatma Gandhi, who led India's independence movement, was born in Porbandar. He developed the concept of Satyagraha, which means truth-force. The Dandi March, which he led in 1930, was a key moment in the freedom struggle. People who followed him came from all walks of life.'\n\n(a) Identify all relative clauses in the passage.\n(b) Which are defining and which are non-defining?\n(c) What does each relative pronoun refer to?\n(d) Rewrite the second sentence by combining it with: 'Satyagraha was practised by millions.'",a:"(a) Relative clauses in the passage:\n1. 'who led India's independence movement' (about Mahatma Gandhi)\n2. 'which means truth-force' (about Satyagraha)\n3. 'which he led in 1930' (about the Dandi March)\n4. 'who followed him' (about people)\n\n(b) Defining vs Non-defining:\n• 'who led India's independence movement' — NON-DEFINING (Gandhi already named, commas used)\n• 'which means truth-force' — NON-DEFINING (Satyagraha already named, commas used)\n• 'which he led in 1930' — NON-DEFINING (Dandi March already named, commas used)\n• 'who followed him' — DEFINING (identifies WHICH people — those who followed him)\n\n(c) What each relative pronoun refers to:\n• First 'who' → Mahatma Gandhi (a person)\n• 'which' (first) → Satyagraha (a concept/thing)\n• 'which' (second) → The Dandi March (an event/thing)\n• Second 'who' → People\n\n(d) Rewritten sentence:\n'He developed the concept of Satyagraha, which means truth-force and was practised by millions.'\nOR: 'He developed the concept of Satyagraha, which means truth-force, and this concept was practised by millions.'"}
      ]
