      short: [
        {q:"Explain the use of 'a', 'an' and 'the' with rules and examples.",a:"USE OF ARTICLES:\n\n'A' — INDEFINITE ARTICLE:\n• Used before singular countable nouns beginning with a CONSONANT SOUND\n• Used when mentioning something for the first time / non-specific\n• Examples: a book, a university (u- has consonant /yoo/ sound), a one-way street\n\n'AN' — INDEFINITE ARTICLE:\n• Used before singular countable nouns beginning with a VOWEL SOUND\n• Examples: an apple, an hour (h is silent → vowel sound), an MBA, an honest man\n\n'THE' — DEFINITE ARTICLE:\n• Used when the noun is specific or already mentioned\n• Used for unique things: the sun, the moon, the earth\n• Used with superlatives: the best, the tallest\n• Used with names of rivers, seas, mountain ranges: the Ganga, the Himalayas\n• Used with musical instruments: play the guitar\n\nNO ARTICLE:\n• Before plural nouns in general: Dogs are loyal (general)\n• Before uncountable nouns in general: Water is essential\n• Before proper nouns (most): India, Delhi, Ravi\n• Before meals, days, months in general: I have breakfast at 8"},
        {q:"Correct the article errors in these sentences:\n(a) She is a honest person.\n(b) I saw a Taj Mahal.\n(c) He plays a piano.\n(d) An university is near my house.",a:"CORRECTED SENTENCES:\n\n(a) ✗ 'She is a honest person.'\n✓ 'She is AN honest person.'\nReason: 'honest' begins with a vowel SOUND (/ɒnɪst/) — 'h' is silent\n\n(b) ✗ 'I saw a Taj Mahal.'\n✓ 'I saw THE Taj Mahal.'\nReason: The Taj Mahal is a unique, specific, well-known monument — use 'the'\n\n(c) ✗ 'He plays a piano.'\n✓ 'He plays THE piano.'\nReason: Musical instruments take 'the' — 'play the guitar/piano/violin'\n\n(d) ✗ 'An university is near my house.'\n✓ 'A university is near my house.'\nReason: 'university' begins with a consonant SOUND (/juːnɪvɜːsɪti/) — 'u' sounds like 'yoo'"}
      ],
      long: [
        {q:"Fill in the blanks with appropriate articles (a/an/the/—) in the following paragraph and explain your choices:\n\n'___ Nile is ___ longest river in ___ world. It flows through ___ Africa. ___ ancient Egyptians built ___ great civilisations along its banks. ___ river has ___ enormous historical importance.'",a:"FILLED PARAGRAPH WITH EXPLANATIONS:\n\n'THE Nile is THE longest river in THE world. It flows through — Africa. THE ancient Egyptians built — great civilisations along its banks. THE river has AN enormous historical importance.'\n\nEXPLANATIONS:\n1. THE Nile → 'the' with names of rivers (the Ganga, the Thames, the Nile)\n2. THE longest → 'the' with superlatives (the longest, the best, the tallest)\n3. THE world → 'the' — unique entity\n4. — Africa → no article before continents (Africa, Asia, Europe)\n5. THE ancient Egyptians → 'the' — specific people (a particular civilisation)\n6. — great civilisations → no article — plural noun, general (OR 'great' = no specific reference)\n7. THE river → 'the' — already mentioned (the Nile, now referred to as 'the river')\n8. AN enormous → 'an' before vowel sound (e- in enormous = vowel sound)"}
      ],
      passage: [
        {q:"Read and find all articles in this passage, then answer questions:\n\n'A young student found an old book in the library. The book contained an interesting story about a great king who lived in an ancient city. The king was famous for his wisdom.'\n\n(a) List all articles used and the nouns they refer to.\n(b) Why is 'a young student' used instead of 'the young student'?\n(c) Why is 'the library' used with 'the'?\n(d) Why is 'an old book' used, not 'a old book'?",a:"(a) Articles and their nouns:\n• A young student — indefinite, first mention\n• an old book — indefinite, first mention\n• the library — definite (specific library)\n• The book — definite (already mentioned)\n• an interesting story — indefinite, first mention\n• a great king — indefinite, first mention\n• an ancient city — indefinite, first mention\n• The king — definite (already mentioned)\n\n(b) 'A young student' not 'the young student' because:\n• It is the FIRST mention — the reader doesn't know which student\n• It's not a specific, identified student known to the reader\n• 'The' would be used if we had already mentioned the student or both speaker and listener know which student\n\n(c) 'The library' uses 'the' because:\n• It refers to a SPECIFIC library — a particular one known in context\n• When there is one library in a school/town, everyone knows which library is meant\n• Specific, known places use 'the'\n\n(d) 'An old book' not 'a old book' because:\n• 'Old' begins with a VOWEL SOUND (/ɒld/)\n• 'An' is used before vowel sounds, regardless of spelling\n• The rule is about SOUND, not spelling"}
      ]
